FROM THE OX'S MOUTH






February 13, 2013

Kent Croft, President of Croft-Leominster and CIO of the Croft FundsRussell Croft, Vice President of Croft-Leominster and Portfolio Manager of the Croft Funds
Manager's Commentary - Agriculture Commentary 
Investment Opportunity: Agriculture Commentary - 1Q 2013 
Increasing demand for food and a  finite supply of land will create pressures leading to investment opportunities  over the long-term. Farmers will be asked to reap more from their limited raw  resources and will need to improve land productivity. Demand for products including  agriculture equipment, irrigation systems, seeds and fertilizers should lead to  many years of growth. This growth will be somewhat independent of other  macroeconomic drivers and can act as a hedge from more volatile economic cycles. Demand Growth: More (Omnivorous) Mouths to Feed Global food consumption is driven  at its core by world population growth. The world’s population exceeded 7  billion in 2012, and baseline estimates released by the U.N. suggest it will  grow approximately 30 percent to 9 billion by 2050, or 0.6 percent annually.  While a sub-1 percent annual growth rate in the key driver of additional food  demand does not by itself offer a compelling argument for large consumption  increases, a confluence of other factors could drive a consumption growth of 70  percent from 2010 to 2050. According to J.P. Morgan, China’s consumption of  major crops grew 31 percent annually from 2001 to 2012 despite total population  growth of roughly 6 percent during the same time period. Wealth gains made  possible by economic advancements in developing markets with relatively large  populations will cause an outward shift of the demand curve for all sources of  foods. Furthermore, as economies develop, dietary regimens shift toward a higher  intake of proteins, and they consume more meat. A multiplier effect occurs on  agriculture demand because significantly more crops are needed as feed in order  to produce meat for human consumption. The Water Footprint Network estimates that  one pound of beef requires roughly 6.6 pounds of grain for feed while a pound  of pork and a pound of chicken require roughly 4 and 2 pounds, respectively.  Biofuels: Food vs. Fuel Demand for agriculture products is  not only increasing as a source of food but also as a source of energy. The  higher cost of fossil fuels and desire for energy independence have driven  significant research into generating energy from renewable sources, one of  which is biofuels. These can be derived from many sources such as corn, sugar,  timber, and grass as well as vegetable oils and animal fats (specifically  referred to as “biodiesels”). The use of biofuels for energy and heat has  experienced only modest penetration rates thus far, yet ethanol still managed  to account for nearly 30 percent of the U.S. corn crop in 2011. U.S. Government  mandates have driven adoption of ethanol/gasoline blends which has made corn  roughly 10 percent of the annual domestic fuel supply. The U.S. represents  roughly 60 percent of the world’s total ethanol production while Brazil is the  other large player with about 20 percent share. Other nations have been slower  to adopt biofuels as a cheaper fuel solution for various reasons, but in a 2011  report the International Energy Agency (IEA) estimated that biofuels have the  potential to account for 27 percent of the world’s demand for transportation  fuels by 2050. While this target may be ambitious, there are real implications  on food prices if significant growth in biofuel demand materializes worldwide  over the next few decades.  Supply Constraints: Doing Less… While incremental demand growth  appears virtually certain, crop supply growth has plateaued over the past  decade with further gains appearing difficult to achieve. Limited supply of  arable land capable of producing crops remains the primary supply growth  inhibitor. Outside of sub-Saharan Africa, there is little remaining  uncultivated land, and what remains is rife with various issues that will  continue to hold back agricultural development.   These include water scarcity, environmental concerns and a lack of  transportation infrastructure. Furthermore, huge yield gains of roughly 150  percent on a per acre basis over the past 50 years because of the use of  advanced fertilizers and agricultural technology leave very little in terms of  low-hanging fruit. Worldwide annual grain productivity gains have fallen from  3.5 percent in 1970 to below 1.5 percent in recent years. The chart below shows  that wheat yields have been flat for over a decade in Germany, France, and the  U.K., while Japanese rice yields have barely grown over the past 15 years.     …With LessProduction growth is not only being  squeezed by limited land and productivity growth, but also by poor farming  practices that have reduced the amount of favorable farmland via erosion and  topsoil loss. One-third of the world’s farmland is at least moderately-degraded  due to dustbowls in important producing regions in China and Africa.  Topsoil is disappearing at five times the  replacement rate in Australia, 10 times in the U.S. and up to 57 times in  China. Extreme weather has been a near-term issue that has created even more  pressure on worldwide supplies. Drought conditions prevail in 65 percent of the  contiguous U.S., and La Niña patterns have created droughts across South  America. Meanwhile, floods in Australia have pressured recent wheat output, and  generally warmer temperatures have hurt yields worldwide. For the 2012-2013  crop year, these factors have resulted in significant reductions to expected  ending grain stocks. This level is now expected to fall below the 2007-2008 crop  year, a time of record high prices. Water: An Inflationary InputBeyond the supply dynamics  mentioned above, water is a major input in all types of agriculture,  representing roughly 70 percent of the world’s freshwater usage annually. Usage  is growing along with crop demand because of similar socioeconomic forces.  However, freshwater represents only about 1  percent of the total worldwide water supply and this ratio is moving in the  wrong direction. Underground aquifers used mainly for agricultural purposes are  being depleted in excess of replacement in many areas. Water shortages due to  pollution, poor infrastructure, inefficient farming practices and other factors  are driving 8 percent average annual price increases in a commodity that was  previously, for all intents and purposes, considered a common good with a  virtually unlimited supply. Pricing pressure has been exacerbated by the multiplicative  effects of the higher protein consumption trend. Not only does it require  larger amounts of grain as feed to produce meat for human consumption, but the increased  water requirements are just as staggering. A pound of beef requires roughly  1,800 gallons of water to reach the dinner table, while wheat is the most water-intensive  major crop at roughly 132 gallons per pound. Investment Opportunities: Companies who Benefit The economic implications of higher crop prices  are vast and create an investable trend over the long-term. We believe that  names directly exposed to the agriculture market stand to benefit significantly  from secularly higher crop demand. On the back of rising crop prices during the  past few years, farmer incomes have nearly doubled, and their balance sheets  are in the best shape ever during the past half century. According to the  Agriculture Department, farmers should generate a net income of over $122  billion in 2012, the highest level since 1973 when adjusting for inflation. The  Kansas City Fed said in November of 2012 that farmland prices were up nearly 25  percent year-over-year for the third quarter hitting all-time records in a  multitude of Midwest states such as Iowa and Minnesota, among others. Excellent  farmer finances combined with the need to grow production and squeeze out  further productivity gains should spur investments in farm equipment,  irrigation systems, advanced fertilizers and other agriculture technology. Deere & Co. should continue to  see robust demand for its farming equipment that can provide large production  gains. Trimble Navigation offers farmers technology that can collect and  analyze data which they can use to automate processes and increase their  overall efficiency. In the fertilizer space, companies such as The Mosaic Co.  and Potash Corp. should benefit from increased demand for their yield-increasing  products. Monsanto Company’s genetically engineered seeds allow farmers to plant  in more areas and lengthen the planting season. FMC Corp. should see continued  demand for their herbicides, insecticides, and fungicides which are all  important contributors to crop yields. Valmont Industries is a leader in  irrigation equipment with a presence in international markets where penetration  is low. Valmont can help solve many of the aforementioned problems by offering  better water efficiency, increased yields, and a reduction in erosion and  topsoil loss.The Destructive Destabilization of Crop Inflation The societal implications of higher  crop prices are quite sobering. Across the world, rising costs will be passed  through to consumers who will see more of their disposable income eaten up at  the grocery store or market. In developed markets, the growth of processed  food, highly efficient supply chains and competition between grocery stores,  restaurants, etc., will help limit the effect on the end user. In developing  markets, however, rising crop prices could drive large increases in food costs  and lead to geopolitical instability. Food accounts for roughly 10 percent of  the budgets of more developed nations versus greater than 40 percent for  emerging countries. Not coincidentally, when the Food and Agriculture  Organization (FAO) food price index spikes above 210 as it did in 2008 and  2011, we see a significant increase in riots and civil unrest. During the 2008  crisis, food prices spiked on a confluence of many of the factors mentioned  above causing unrest in countries across Asia and Africa. In 2011, rising food  costs were a major factor in setting off the Arab Spring, which caused riots  across the Middle East and the demise of regimes in Egypt, Yemen, Tunisia and  Libya. Such turmoil could derail economic advancement in these fragile nations  and limit overall global GDP growth.  Long-term Threats and Opportunities Food demand per capita is growing  along with the world’s population, yet there will be no concurrent growth in  either the earth’s size or raw resources. Unless investments are made to both  increase the productivity and maintain the supply of land, there will be serious  worldwide consequences and potentially crippling socioeconomic instability. Providers  of solutions that help farmers economically and efficiently attain these goals  are attractive investments on a long-term horizon. The inelastic nature of food  demand should drive increased use of these companies’ products and services  under various macroeconomic conditions leading to less correlation and  volatility versus the general equity indices over time.Risks to our thesis on food demand  growth include slower worldwide population and GDP growth, especially in  emerging economies. An end or reduction of ethanol mandates would likely  diminish overall demand for corn and create downward pressure on crop prices.  Also, a long period of favorable weather could lead to significant oversupply  of crops which would depress prices and limit farmer investments. Information in this commentary regarding market or economic trends or  the factors influencing historical or future performance reflects the opinions  of management as of the date hereof.  These statements should not be  relied upon for any other purpose. Past performance is no guarantee of future  results, and there is no guarantee that any market forecast or trend discussed  herein will be realized. Although the information presented herein is based on  sources believed to be reliable, such information is not guaranteed to be  accurate and is subject to change. This material should not be used as a primary basis for making  investment decisions. Consider your own financial circumstances and goals  carefully before making any investment decision. 



